Etiam maior est, ete The read- ing of the MSS. here cau hardly be de- fended. The only natural translation is ‘still greater (i. e. more important) is the practice,' etc. Greater than what? Than amplificatio. But it is one means of amplificatio, a species under the genus, with which it cannot therefore be com· pared. Ell.'s note—‘ cavendum ne cum sono pronuntiemus maior, re prona prop· ter additum etiam'—recognises the diffi- culty, but does not do much to remove it. The attempt has been made to interpret ‘etiam' as ‘further' and ‘maior' as ‘rather important,' which is quite inconsistent with ‘nihil est . .. accommodatius?
